---
description: General clean-code rules for all files
alwaysApply: true
---

Write clear, boring, maintainable code.

Rules:
- Prefer simple code over clever abstractions.
- Keep functions small.
- Use descriptive names.
- Avoid duplicated logic.
- Avoid deep nesting.
- Keep side effects isolated.
- Do not rewrite unrelated code.
- Do not introduce new dependencies unless clearly justified.
- Do not hide failures.
- Do not remove error handling only to simplify code.
- When uncertain, choose readability.

For deeper review, see rule 006 and `.cursor/rules/external/ciembor/clean-code.mini.md`.
For design depth principles, see `.cursor/rules/external/ciembor/philosophy-of-software-design.mini.md`.
